ings, Foxton and Weller, but released under artist name \"Bruce Foxton\".\n\n==Further reading==\nEgan, Sean (2018). ''Love With a Passion Called Hate: The Inside Story of The Jam''. London: Askill Publishing. {{ISBN|978-0-9545750-9-0}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thejamfan.net/ The Jam fan site \u2013 As run by Rick Buckler]\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/23228f18-01d5-493e-94ce-cfcde82a8db2 The Jam at the BBC]\n*[http://arts.guardian.co.uk/filmandmusic/story/0,,1700386,00.html Guardian article about The Jam]\n*[http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1054714/two-thirds-of-the-jam-reuniting-for-tour Billboard.com article about 'From the Jam']\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/jul/15/books.musicnews Vanessa Thorpe, 25 years on, life in the Jam is revealed, Guardian/Observer, 15 July 2007]\n*[http://www.thejam.org.uk/ The Jam Information Pages (thejam.org.uk). Extensive history, lyrics, album covers, info on The Jam']\n*[http://www.zani.co.uk/thick-as-thieves-personal-situations-with-the-jam-full-documentary Documentary on The Jam 2012]\n*[http://www.fromthejamofficial.com/ The Official From the Jam site Administrated by Guy Helliker]\n{{The Jam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jam, The}}\n[[Category:The Jam| ]]\n[[Category:English new wave musical groups]]\n[[Category:English punk rock groups]]\n[[Category:British mod revival groups]]\n[[Category:English power pop groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1982]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1972]]\n[[Category:British musical trios]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Surrey]]\n[[Category:Polydor Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:DATEUNIFY (audit)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Jam"}
{"title_page": "Andrej Kiska", "text_new": "{{short description|4th President of Slovakia}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Andrej Kiska\n| image = Andrej Kiska Senate of Slowakia.jpg\n| office = 4th [[President of Slovakia]]\n| primeminister = [[Robert Fico]]<br />[[Peter Pellegrini]]\n| term_start = 15 June 2014\n| term_end = 15 June 2019\n| predecessor = [[Ivan Ga\u0161parovi\u010d]]\n| successor = [[Zuzana \u010caputov\u00e1]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|2|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Poprad]], [[Czechoslovakia]]<br />{{small|(now [[Slovakia]])}}\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[For the People (political party)|Za \u013eud\u00ed]] (2019\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dennikn.sk/1486837/kiska-spustil-bilbordovu-predkampan-na-svoju-stranu-ma-slogan-vratme-slovensko-vsetkym-ludom/|title=Kiska spustil bilbordov\u00fa predkampa\u0148 na svoju stranu. M\u00e1 slogan \u201eVr\u00e1\u0165me Slovensko v\u0161etk\u00fdm \u013eu\u010fom\u201c|first=Du\u0161an|last=Miku\u0161ovi\u010d|date=June 1, 2019|website=Denn\u00edk N}}</ref>\n| otherparty = [[Independent Politician|Independent]] (2014\u20132019)\n| spouse = {{marriage|{{Interlanguage link|M\u00e1ria Kiskov\u00e1|sk}}|1985|2001|end=div.}}<br />{{marriage|[[Martina Kiskov\u00e1|Martina \u017divorov\u00e1]]|2001}}\n| children = 5\n| alma_mater = [[Slovak University of Technology in Bratislava|Slovak University of<br />Technology]]\n| website = {{url|https://za-ludi.sk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Andrej Kiska''' ({{IPA-sk|\u02c8andr\u025bj \u02c8kiska}}; born 2 February 1963) is a Slovak politician, entrepreneur, writer  and philanthropist who was [[President of Slovakia]] from 2014 to 2019. He ran as an [[independent (politician)|independent candidate]] in the [[2014 Slovak presidential election|2014 presidential election]] and was elected as President in the second round of voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/03/16/uk-slovakia-election-idUKBREA2F00V20140316|title= Slovak PM Fico, political novice advance to run-off presidential vote|date=16 March 2014|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/zahranici/evropa/slovaci-voli-prezidenta-fica-ohrozuje-filantrop-kiska_300966.html#.UyV-V84m-t8|title=Slov\u00e1ci vol\u00ed prezidenta. Fica ohro\u017euje filantrop Kiska|date=15 March 2014 |publisher=T\u00fdden|language=Czech|accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.topky.sk/cl/1000735/1375311/Kandidat-na-prezidenta-Andrej-Kiska--Najvyssim-zmyslom-zivota-je-pomahat-druhym- | title=Kandid\u00e1t na prezidenta Andrej Kiska: Najvy\u0161\u0161\u00edm zmyslom \u017eivota je pom\u00e1ha\u0165 druh\u00fdm! | publisher=Topky.sk | accessdate=March 16, 2014 | language=Slovak}}</ref> He has written two books about happiness, success and his life.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early and personal life===\nKiska was born in [[Poprad]]. He studied [[electrical engineering]]. His father was an active member of the ruling Communist Party of Czechoslovakia. He also applied for Communist party membership, but was rejected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://domov.sme.sk/c/7154011/podnikatel-filantrop-a-uz-aj-prezident-andrej-kiska.html|title=Podnikate\u013e, filantrop a u\u017e aj prezident. Andrej Kiska|first=Petit Press|last=a.s|website=domov.sme.sk}}</ref>\n\nKiska was married to {{Interlanguage link|M\u00e1ria Kiskov\u00e1|sk}}, an educator and politician from 1985 until 2001. They had two children, Andrej Kiska (1986) and Nat\u00e1lia Kiskov\u00e1 (1990).<ref name=ssp>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=President Kiska has a new baby son |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/20578740/president-kiska-has-a-new-baby-son.html |work=The Slovak Spectator |date=2017-07-10 |accessdate=2018-08-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117161812/http://www.pluska.sk/spravy/z-domova/prva-dama-martina-kiskova-co-odkazuje-vsetkym-neprajnikom.html |archivedate=2014-11-17 |url-status = live|df= }}</ref> The couple divorced in 2001 after 18 years of marriage.\n\nKiska married his second wife, [[Martina Kiskov\u00e1]], in 2003. The couple have three children- - Veronika (born 2005), Viktor (born 2009), and Martin (born July 2017 during his presidency).<ref name=ssp/>\n\n===Career===\nIn 1990, after the [[Velvet Revolution]], he moved to the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novinky.cz/zahranicni/evropa/331929-novym-slovenskym-prezidentem-bude-andrej-kiska.html|title=Nov\u00fdm slovensk\u00fdm prezidentem bude Andrej Kiska|date=29 March 2014|publisher=[[novinky.cz]]|language=Czech|accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> Later he founded ''Triangel'' and ''Quatro'',<ref name=\"databazeknih\">{{cite web | url=http://www.databazeknih.cz/zivotopis/andrej-kiska-23188 | title=Andrej Kiska - \u017eivotopis | publisher=DatabazeKnih | accessdate=March 17, 2014 | language=Slovak}}</ref> two Slovakia-based [[hire-purchase]] companies that give the buyer the possibility to pay for goods in several installments over a number of months instead of paying the full price at once.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.investopedia.com/terms/h/hire-purchase.asp | title=Hire-purchase definition | publisher=Investopedia | accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nTax authorities accused his co-owned company KTAG (with his brother Jaroslav) of tax non-compliance and under-payments, regarding expenses for his presidential campaign. The company eventually agreed to pay the taxes and a penalty.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://slovensko.hnonline.sk/1025396-kiska-sklamal-transparency-vyhovorky-mal-prijat-zodpovednost-a-ospravedlnit-sa|title=Kiska sklamal Transparency: V\u00fdhovorky, mal prija\u0165 zodpovednos\u0165 a ospravedlni\u0165 sa|website=slovensko.hnonline.sk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://domov.sme.sk/c/20647309/kiska-bol-som-presvedceny-ze-firma-kona-spravne.html|title=Kiska: Bol som presved\u010den\u00fd, \u017ee firma kon\u00e1 spr\u00e1vne|first=Petit Press|last=a.s|website=domov.sme.sk}}</ref>\n\n=== Tax non-compliance and legal problems===\n\nAndrej Kiska's companies were involved in a number of tax-non compliance issues. Improperly reported income from various business activities resulted in a smaller VAT and Income tax payments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spravy.pravda.sk/domace/clanok/441545-otazky-a-odpovede-v-com-spociva-trestna-cinnost-v-kauze-kiskovej-firmy/|title=Ot\u00e1zky a odpovede: V \u010dom spo\u010d\u00edva trestn\u00e1 \u010dinnos\u0165 v kauze Kiskovej firmy?|date=September 13, 2017|website=Pravda.sk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nazory.pravda.sk/komentare-a-glosy/clanok/441818-kiska-bez-svatoziary/|title=Kiska bez sv\u00e4to\u017eiary|date=September 16, 2017|website=Pravda.sk}}</ref>\n\nIn his personal tax filing he did not disclose personal propagation before elections performed by his company as a non-cash income, but claimed that he paid for it. Eventually tax office confirmed he did not pay, did not report non-cash income, and his company did not report income from propagation activities but fully deducted all VAT. Remaining costs additionally decreased tax base.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://domov.sme.sk/c/20649096/tlak-na-kisku-sa-stupnuje-unikli-dalsie-dokumenty.html|title=Tlak na Kisku sa stup\u0148uje, unikli \u010fal\u0161ie dokumenty|first=Petit Press|last=a.s|website=domov.sme.sk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slovensko.hnonline.sk/1025081-kisku-vysetrovala-policia-pre-vydavky-na-kampan-prezident-reagoval-na-obvinenie|title=Kisku vy\u0161etrovala pol\u00edcia pre v\u00fddavky na kampa\u0148, prezident reagoval na obvinenie|website=slovensko.hnonline.sk}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nIn 2006, Kiska co-founded a [[non-profit]] [[charitable organization]] called [[Dobr\u00fd anjel]] (translated as ''Good Angel''), in which donors help families that have found themselves in a difficult financial situation as a result of a family member contracting a serious disease (such as [[cancer]]).<ref name=\"databazeknih\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dobryanjel.sk/viac-o-dobrom-anjelovi/ |title=\u010co je syst\u00e9m Dobr\u00fd anjel | publisher=Dobr\u00fd anjel |accessdate=March 17, 2014 |language=Slovak}}</ref> By 2016, more than 170,000 people have donated to this organization in Slovakia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dobryanjel.sk/zoznam-dobrych-anjelov/|title=Zoznam Dobr\u00fdch anjelov|last=|first=|date=March 1, 2014|website=|publisher=Dobr\u00fd anjel|language=Slovak|access-date=|accessdate=August 9, 2016}}</ref> In 2014 Good Angel expanded their activities also to Czech Republic, where 60.000 are paying their monthly contributions in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dobryandel.cz/en/|title=DOBR\u00dd AND\u011aL, nadace|website=DOBR\u00dd AND\u011aL|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-09}}</ref> In addition to that, Kiska donates his monthly presidential salary to people in need.\n\n==Presidency==\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets with Slovak President Kiska (46347493364).jpg|thumb|Kiska (right) with US Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] in February 2019]]\nIn the first round of the [[2014 Slovak presidential election]], Kiska placed second with 24% of the vote, behind Prime Minister [[Robert Fico]] (28%). As none of candidates got more than 50% of votes, Kiska and Fico progressed to a presidential runoff vote on 29 March 2014. With the support of right-wing parties and other defeated candidates, Kiska won decisively in the second round, receiving nearly 60% of the vote.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/slovakia/10732435/Millionaire-Andrej-Kiska-elected-first-Slovak-president-with-no-communist-past.html \"Millionaire Andrej Kiska elected first Slovak president with no communist past\"], ''[[Telegraph Online]]'', 30 March 2014, accessed 30 March 2014.</ref> He took office on 15 June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.europeonline-magazine.eu/andrej-kiska-inaugurated-as-slovakian-president_341202.html|title=Andrej Kiska inaugurated as Slovakian president|date=15 June 2014|publisher=Europe Online Magazine|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nKiska announced on 15 May 2018 that he will not participate in [[2019 Slovak presidential election|2019 presidential election]], arguing that his departure might end \"the era of political confrontation\" his country faced and citing a desire to spend more time with his family.<ref name=\"Kiska nebude kandidova\u0165 na prezidenta\">{{cite web|title=Kiska nebude kandidova\u0165 na prezidenta|url=https://domov.sme.sk/c/20826159/andrej-kiska-prezidentske-volby-2019-oznamenie.html?ref=st-bno-1|website=domov.sme.sk|accessdate=15 May 2018|language=sk}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-15/eu-to-lose-key-ally-in-slovakia-as-president-won-t-seek-new-term|title=EU to Lose Key Ally in Slovakia as President Won't Seek New Term|date=2018-05-15|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> At the time Kiska made the announcement, polls indicated that he was Slovakia's most trusted politician and that he would have likely been the frontrunner in the election had he chosen to present himself as a candidate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Foreign policy===\nKiska supports [[Kosovo independence]] and is in favour of Slovakia diplomatically [[International recognition of Kosovo|recognising]] [[Kosovo]] as an independent sovereign state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/info/vesti/index.php?yyyy=2014&mm=03&dd=30&nav_category=78&nav_id=830326|title=Milioner na \u010delu Slova\u010dke|date=2014-03-30|accessdate=2014-03-31|publisher=[[B92]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/ausland/article126354035/Parteiloser-Millionaer-wird-slowakischer-Praesident.html|title=Parteiloser Million\u00e4r wird slowakischer Pr\u00e4sident|accessdate=2014-03-31|publisher=[[Die Welt]]}}</ref>\n\nKiska has also come out against Russia over the Ukraine conflict and supports [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.praguepost.com/eu-news/40949-slovak-president-rejects-pm-s-negative-view-of-russian-sanctions |title=Slovak president rejects PM\u2019s negative view of Russian sanctions |date=2014-08-15 |accessdate=2015-04-02 |publisher=[[The Prague Post]] |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402052915/http://praguepost.com/eu-news/40949-slovak-president-rejects-pm-s-negative-view-of-russian-sanctions |archivedate=2015-04-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/slovak-president-kiska-eu-must-stand-united-on-russia-1423073916|title=Slovak President Kiska: EU Must Stand United on Russia|date=2015-02-04|accessdate=2015-04-02|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uatoday.tv/politics/slovakian-president-andrej-kiska-meets-with-nato-secretary-general-jens-stoltenberg-413090.html|title=Slovakian President Andrej Kiska meets with NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg|date=2015-03-03|accessdate=2015-04-02|publisher=[[Ukraine Today]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20056584/president-will-not-go-to-moscow.html|title=President will not go to Moscow|date=2015-03-18|accessdate=2015-04-02|publisher=[[The Slovak Spectator]]}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: [[Order of the White Double Cross]]\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: [[Order of \u013dudov\u00edt \u0160t\u00far]]\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: [[Pribina Cross]]\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Slovakia|Order of Andrej Hlinka]]\n\n===Foreign honours===\n* {{flag|Austria}}: Grand Star of the [[Decoration of Honour for Services to the Republic of Austria]]\n* {{flag|Estonia}}: Collar of the [[Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.president.ee/en/estonia/decorations/bearer/19319/andrej-kiska/|title=Vabariigi President|website=www.president.ee}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Germany}}: Grand Cross Special Class of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n* {{flag|Monaco}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Saint-Charles]]\n* {{flag|Norway}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of St. Olav]]\n* {{flag|Romania}}: Collar of the [[Order of the Star of Romania]]\n* {{flag|Poland}}: Knight of the [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Andrej Kiska}}\n*{{Official website}} {{in lang|sk}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ivan Ga\u0161parovi\u010d]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Slovakia]]|years=2014\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Zuzana \u010caputov\u00e1]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SlovakPresidents}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kiska, Andrej}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Poprad]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Slovak businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Slovak Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Slovak University of Technology in Bratislava alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Collar of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|4th President of Slovakia}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Andrej Kiska\n| image = Andrej Kiska Senate of Slowakia.jpg\n| office = 4th [[President of Slovakia]]\n| primeminister = [[Robert Fico]]<br />[[Peter Pellegrini]]\n| term_start = 15 June 2014\n| term_end = 15 June 2019\n| predecessor = [[Ivan Ga\u0161parovi\u010d]]\n| successor = [[Zuzana \u010caputov\u00e1]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|2|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Poprad]], [[Czechoslovakia]]<br />{{small|(now [[Slovakia]])}}\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[For the People (political party)|Za \u013eud\u00ed]] (2019\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dennikn.sk/1486837/kiska-spustil-bilbordovu-predkampan-na-svoju-stranu-ma-slogan-vratme-slovensko-vsetkym-ludom/|title=Kiska spustil bilbordov\u00fa predkampa\u0148 na svoju stranu. M\u00e1 slogan \u201eVr\u00e1\u0165me Slovensko v\u0161etk\u00fdm \u013eu\u010fom\u201c|first=Du\u0161an|last=Miku\u0161ovi\u010d|date=June 1, 2019|website=Denn\u00edk N}}</ref>\n| otherparty = [[Independent Politician|Independent]] (2014\u20132019)\n| spouse = {{marriage|{{Interlanguage link|M\u00e1ria Kiskov\u00e1|sk}}|1985|2001|end=div.}}<br />{{marriage|[[Martina Kiskov\u00e1|Martina \u017divorov\u00e1]]|2001}}\n| children = 5\n| alma_mater = [[Slovak University of Technology in Bratislava|Slovak University of<br />Technology]]\n| website = {{url|https://za-ludi.sk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Andrej Kiska''' ({{IPA-sk|\u02c8andr\u025bj \u02c8kiska}}; born 2 February 1963) is a Slovak politician, entrepreneur, writer  and philanthropist who was [[President of Slovakia]] from 2014 to 2019. He ran as an [[independent (politician)|independent candidate]] in the [[2014 Slovak presidential election|2014 presidential election]] and was elected as President in the second round of voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/03/16/uk-slovakia-election-idUKBREA2F00V20140316|title= Slovak PM Fico, political novice advance to run-off presidential vote|date=16 March 2014|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/zahranici/evropa/slovaci-voli-prezidenta-fica-ohrozuje-filantrop-kiska_300966.html#.UyV-V84m-t8|title=Slov\u00e1ci vol\u00ed prezidenta. Fica ohro\u017euje filantrop Kiska|date=15 March 2014 |publisher=T\u00fdden|language=Czech|accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.topky.sk/cl/1000735/1375311/Kandidat-na-prezidenta-Andrej-Kiska--Najvyssim-zmyslom-zivota-je-pomahat-druhym- | title=Kandid\u00e1t na prezidenta Andrej Kiska: Najvy\u0161\u0161\u00edm zmyslom \u017eivota je pom\u00e1ha\u0165 druh\u00fdm! | publisher=Topky.sk | accessdate=March 16, 2014 | language=Slovak}}</ref> He has written two books about happiness, success and his life.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early and personal life===\nKiska was born in [[Poprad]]. He studied [[electrical engineering]]. His father was an active member of the ruling Communist Party of Czechoslovakia. He also applied for Communist party membership, but was rejected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://domov.sme.sk/c/7154011/podnikatel-filantrop-a-uz-aj-prezident-andrej-kiska.html|title=Podnikate\u013e, filantrop a u\u017e aj prezident. Andrej Kiska|first=Petit Press|last=a.s|website=domov.sme.sk}}</ref>\n\nKiska was married to {{Interlanguage link|M\u00e1ria Kiskov\u00e1|sk}}, an educator and politician from 1985 until 2001. They had two children, Andrej Kiska (1986) and Nat\u00e1lia Kiskov\u00e1 (1990).<ref name=ssp>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=President Kiska has a new baby son |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/20578740/president-kiska-has-a-new-baby-son.html |work=The Slovak Spectator |date=2017-07-10 |accessdate=2018-08-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117161812/http://www.pluska.sk/spravy/z-domova/prva-dama-martina-kiskova-co-odkazuje-vsetkym-neprajnikom.html |archivedate=2014-11-17 |url-status = live|df= }}</ref> The couple divorced in 2001 after 18 years of marriage.\n\nKiska married his second wife, [[Martina Kiskov\u00e1]], in 2003. The couple have three children- - Veronika (born 2005), Viktor (born 2009), and Martin (born July 2017 during his presidency).<ref name=ssp/>\n\n===Career===\nIn 1990, after the [[Velvet Revolution]], he moved to the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novinky.cz/zahranicni/evropa/331929-novym-slovenskym-prezidentem-bude-andrej-kiska.html|title=Nov\u00fdm slovensk\u00fdm prezidentem bude Andrej Kiska|date=29 March 2014|publisher=[[novinky.cz]]|language=Czech|accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> Later he founded ''Triangel'' and ''Quatro'',<ref name=\"databazeknih\">{{cite web | url=http://www.databazeknih.cz/zivotopis/andrej-kiska-23188 | title=Andrej Kiska - \u017eivotopis | publisher=DatabazeKnih | accessdate=March 17, 2014 | language=Slovak}}</ref> two Slovakia-based [[hire-purchase]] companies that give the buyer the possibility to pay for goods in several installments over a number of months instead of paying the full price at once.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.investopedia.com/terms/h/hire-purchase.asp | title=Hire-purchase definition | publisher=Investopedia | accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nTax authorities accused his co-owned company KTAG (with his brother Jaroslav) of tax non-compliance and under-payments, regarding expenses for his presidential campaign. The company eventually agreed to pay the taxes and a penalty.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://slovensko.hnonline.sk/1025396-kiska-sklamal-transparency-vyhovorky-mal-prijat-zodpovednost-a-ospravedlnit-sa|title=Kiska sklamal Transparency: V\u00fdhovorky, mal prija\u0165 zodpovednos\u0165 a ospravedlni\u0165 sa|website=slovensko.hnonline.sk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://domov.sme.sk/c/20647309/kiska-bol-som-presvedceny-ze-firma-kona-spravne.html|title=Kiska: Bol som presved\u010den\u00fd, \u017ee firma kon\u00e1 spr\u00e1vne|first=Petit Press|last=a.s|website=domov.sme.sk}}</ref>\n\n=== Tax non-compliance and legal problems===\n\nAndrej Kiska's companies were involved in a number of tax-non compliance issues. Unproperly reported income from various business activities resulted in a smaller VAT and Income tax payments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spravy.pravda.sk/domace/clanok/441545-otazky-a-odpovede-v-com-spociva-trestna-cinnost-v-kauze-kiskovej-firmy/|title=Ot\u00e1zky a odpovede: V \u010dom spo\u010d\u00edva trestn\u00e1 \u010dinnos\u0165 v kauze Kiskovej firmy?|date=September 13, 2017|website=Pravda.sk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nazory.pravda.sk/komentare-a-glosy/clanok/441818-kiska-bez-svatoziary/|title=Kiska bez sv\u00e4to\u017eiary|date=September 16, 2017|website=Pravda.sk}}</ref>\n\nIn his personal tax filing he did not disclose personal propagation before elections performed by his company as a non-cash income, but claimed that he paid for it. Eventually tax office confirmed he did not pay, did not report non-cash income, and his company did not report income from propagation activities but fully deducted all VAT. Remaining costs additionally decreased tax base.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://domov.sme.sk/c/20649096/tlak-na-kisku-sa-stupnuje-unikli-dalsie-dokumenty.html|title=Tlak na Kisku sa stup\u0148uje, unikli \u010fal\u0161ie dokumenty|first=Petit Press|last=a.s|website=domov.sme.sk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slovensko.hnonline.sk/1025081-kisku-vysetrovala-policia-pre-vydavky-na-kampan-prezident-reagoval-na-obvinenie|title=Kisku vy\u0161etrovala pol\u00edcia pre v\u00fddavky na kampa\u0148, prezident reagoval na obvinenie|website=slovensko.hnonline.sk}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nIn 2006, Kiska co-founded a [[non-profit]] [[charitable organization]] called [[Dobr\u00fd anjel]] (translated as ''Good Angel''), in which donors help families that have found themselves in a difficult financial situation as a result of a family member contracting a serious disease (such as [[cancer]]).<ref name=\"databazeknih\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dobryanjel.sk/viac-o-dobrom-anjelovi/ |title=\u010co je syst\u00e9m Dobr\u00fd anjel | publisher=Dobr\u00fd anjel |accessdate=March 17, 2014 |language=Slovak}}</ref> By 2016, more than 170,000 people have donated to this organization in Slovakia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dobryanjel.sk/zoznam-dobrych-anjelov/|title=Zoznam Dobr\u00fdch anjelov|last=|first=|date=March 1, 2014|website=|publisher=Dobr\u00fd anjel|language=Slovak|access-date=|accessdate=August 9, 2016}}</ref> In 2014 Good Angel expanded their activities also to Czech Republic, where 60.000 are paying their monthly contributions in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dobryandel.cz/en/|title=DOBR\u00dd AND\u011aL, nadace|website=DOBR\u00dd AND\u011aL|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-09}}</ref> In addition to that, Kiska donates his monthly presidential salary to people in need.\n\n==Presidency==\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets with Slovak President Kiska (46347493364).jpg|thumb|Kiska (right) with US Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] in February 2019]]\nIn the first round of the [[2014 Slovak presidential election]], Kiska placed second with 24% of the vote, behind Prime Minister [[Robert Fico]] (28%). As none of candidates got more than 50% of votes, Kiska and Fico progressed to a presidential runoff vote on 29 March 2014. With the support of right-wing parties and other defeated candidates, Kiska won decisively in the second round, receiving nearly 60% of the vote.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/slovakia/10732435/Millionaire-Andrej-Kiska-elected-first-Slovak-president-with-no-communist-past.html \"Millionaire Andrej Kiska elected first Slovak president with no communist past\"], ''[[Telegraph Online]]'', 30 March 2014, accessed 30 March 2014.</ref> He took office on 15 June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.europeonline-magazine.eu/andrej-kiska-inaugurated-as-slovakian-president_341202.html|title=Andrej Kiska inaugurated as Slovakian president|date=15 June 2014|publisher=Europe Online Magazine|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nKiska announced on 15 May 2018 that he will not participate in [[2019 Slovak presidential election|2019 presidential election]], arguing that his departure might end \"the era of political confrontation\" his country faced and citing a desire to spend more time with his family.<ref name=\"Kiska nebude kandidova\u0165 na prezidenta\">{{cite web|title=Kiska nebude kandidova\u0165 na prezidenta|url=https://domov.sme.sk/c/20826159/andrej-kiska-prezidentske-volby-2019-oznamenie.html?ref=st-bno-1|website=domov.sme.sk|accessdate=15 May 2018|language=sk}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-15/eu-to-lose-key-ally-in-slovakia-as-president-won-t-seek-new-term|title=EU to Lose Key Ally in Slovakia as President Won't Seek New Term|date=2018-05-15|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> At the time Kiska made the announcement, polls indicated that he was Slovakia's most trusted politician and that he would have likely been the frontrunner in the election had he chosen to present himself as a candidate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Foreign policy===\nKiska supports [[Kosovo independence]] and is in favour of Slovakia diplomatically [[International recognition of Kosovo|recognising]] [[Kosovo]] as an independent sovereign state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/info/vesti/index.php?yyyy=2014&mm=03&dd=30&nav_category=78&nav_id=830326|title=Milioner na \u010delu Slova\u010dke|date=2014-03-30|accessdate=2014-03-31|publisher=[[B92]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/ausland/article126354035/Parteiloser-Millionaer-wird-slowakischer-Praesident.html|title=Parteiloser Million\u00e4r wird slowakischer Pr\u00e4sident|accessdate=2014-03-31|publisher=[[Die Welt]]}}</ref>\n\nKiska has also come out against Russia over the Ukraine conflict and supports [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.praguepost.com/eu-news/40949-slovak-president-rejects-pm-s-negative-view-of-russian-sanctions |title=Slovak president rejects PM\u2019s negative view of Russian sanctions |date=2014-08-15 |accessdate=2015-04-02 |publisher=[[The Prague Post]] |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402052915/http://praguepost.com/eu-news/40949-slovak-president-rejects-pm-s-negative-view-of-russian-sanctions |archivedate=2015-04-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/slovak-president-kiska-eu-must-stand-united-on-russia-1423073916|title=Slovak President Kiska: EU Must Stand United on Russia|date=2015-02-04|accessdate=2015-04-02|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uatoday.tv/politics/slovakian-president-andrej-kiska-meets-with-nato-secretary-general-jens-stoltenberg-413090.html|title=Slovakian President Andrej Kiska meets with NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg|date=2015-03-03|accessdate=2015-04-02|publisher=[[Ukraine Today]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20056584/president-will-not-go-to-moscow.html|title=President will not go to Moscow|date=2015-03-18|accessdate=2015-04-02|publisher=[[The Slovak Spectator]]}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: [[Order of the White Double Cross]]\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: [[Order of \u013dudov\u00edt \u0160t\u00far]]\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: [[Pribina Cross]]\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Slovakia|Order of Andrej Hlinka]]\n\n===Foreign honours===\n* {{flag|Austria}}: Grand Star of the [[Decoration of Honour for Services to the Republic of Austria]]\n* {{flag|Estonia}}: Collar of the [[Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.president.ee/en/estonia/decorations/bearer/19319/andrej-kiska/|title=Vabariigi President|website=www.president.ee}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Germany}}: Grand Cross Special Class of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n* {{flag|Monaco}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Saint-Charles]]\n* {{flag|Norway}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of St. Olav]]\n* {{flag|Romania}}: Collar of the [[Order of the Star of Romania]]\n* {{flag|Poland}}: Knight of the [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Andrej Kiska}}\n*{{Official website}} {{in lang|sk}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ivan Ga\u0161parovi\u010d]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Slovakia]]|years=2014\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Zuzana \u010caputov\u00e1]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SlovakPresidents}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kiska, Andrej}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Poprad]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Slovak businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Slovak Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Slovak University of Technology in Bratislava alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Collar of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTax non-compliance and legal problems:Cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrej_Kiska"}
{"title_page": "Ozymandias", "text_new": "{{about|the poems}}\n{{short description|Sonnets written by Shelley and Horace Smith}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox poem\n|name                = Ozymandias (John Cena)\n|image               = Ozymandias The Examiner 1818.jpg\n|image_size          = <!-- custom size for image (defaults to 220px)   -->\n|caption             = Shelley's \"Ozymandias\" in [[The Examiner (1808\u201386)|''The Examiner'']]\n|subtitle            = <!-- Subtitle or descriptor                      -->\n|author              = [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]\n|original_title      = <!-- Original title, if not in English           -->\n|original_title_lang = <!-- ISO 639-2 language code for original title, e.g. \"fr\" for French -->\n|translator          = <!-- Translator(s), if original not in English   -->\n|written             = <!-- Written: (date or year range)               -->\n|first               = 11 January 1818\n|illustrator         = <!-- Illustrator used consistently throughout\n                            (where illustrations are a major feature)   -->\n|cover_artist        = <!-- Cover Artist                                -->\n|country             = [[England]]\n|language            = [[Modern English]]\n|series              = <!-- Series (if any)                             -->\n|subject             = <!-- Subject(/s)                                 -->\n|genre               = <!-- Genre(/s) (only use for fiction)            -->\n|form                = [[Sonnet]]\n|meter               = Loose [[iambic pentameter]]\n|rhyme               = ABABA CDCEDEFEF\n|publisher           = [[The Examiner (1808\u201386)|''The Examiner'']]\n|publication_date    = <!-- Date published (1st edition). Use \n                            {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}, trimmed as needed. -->\n|publication_date_en = <!-- Published in English (1st English edition)  -->\n|media_type          = <!-- MMedia type (paperback, hardback)           -->\n|lines               = <!-- Number of lines in the poem \n                            (prefer 1st edition)                        -->\n|pages               = <!-- Pages (prefer 1st edition)                  -->\n|size_weight         = <!-- Size and Weight                             -->\n|isbn                = <!-- [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] -->\n|oclc                = <!-- [[OCLC]]                                    -->\n|preceded_by         = <!-- Preceded By\n                            Title of prior poem in series               -->\n|followed_by         = <!-- Followed By\n                            Title of subsequent poem in series          -->\n|wikisource          = Ozymandias (Shelley)\n}}\n{{Infobox poem\n|name                = Ozymandias (Smith)\n|image               = <!-- Image (prefer 1st edition - where permitted)\n                            Use the Image Filename (eg: Example.png)    -->\n|image_size          = <!-- custom size for image (defaults to 220px)   -->\n|caption             = <!-- Image caption\n                            (should describe the edition used)          -->\n|subtitle            = <!-- Subtitle or descriptor                      -->\n|author              = [[Horace Smith (poet)|Horace Smith]]\n|original_title      = <!-- Original title, if not in English           -->\n|original_title_lang = <!-- ISO 639-2 language code for original title, e.g. \"fr\" for French -->\n|translator          = <!-- Translator(s), if original not in English   -->\n|written             = <!-- Written: (date or year range)               -->\n|first               = 1 February 1818\n|illustrator         = <!-- Illustrator used consistently throughout\n                            (where illustrations are a major feature)   -->\n|cover_artist        = <!-- Cover Artist                                -->\n|country             = [[England]]\n|language            = <!-- Language of original poem (see note below)  -->\n|series              = <!-- Series (if any)                             -->\n|subject             = <!-- Subject(/s)                                 -->\n|genre               = <!-- Genre(/s) (only use for fiction)            -->\n|form                = [[Sonnet]]\n|meter               = <!-- Meter: (i.e. iambic pentameter)             -->\n|rhyme               = <!-- Rhyme scheme: (i.e. abba cddc effe gg)      -->\n|publisher           = [[The Examiner (1808\u201386)|''The Examiner'']]\n|publication_date    = <!-- Date published (1st edition). Use \n                            {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}, trimmed as needed. -->\n|publication_date_en = <!-- Published in English (1st English edition)  -->\n|media_type          = <!-- MMedia type (paperback, hardback)           -->\n|lines               = <!-- Number of lines in the poem \n                            (prefer 1st edition)                        -->\n|pages               = <!-- Pages (prefer 1st edition)                  -->\n|size_weight         = <!-- Size and Weight                             -->\n|isbn                = <!-- [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] -->\n|oclc                = <!-- [[OCLC]]                                    -->\n|preceded_by         = <!-- Preceded By\n                            Title of prior poem in series               -->\n|followed_by         = <!-- Followed By\n                            Title of subsequent poem in series          -->\n|wikisource          = Ozymandias (Smith)\n}}\n\n\"'''Ozymandias'''\" ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0252|z|i|\u02c8|m|\u00e6|n|d|i|\u0259|s}} {{respell|oz-ee|MAN|dee-\u0259s}})<ref>{{cite book|last=Wells|first=John C.|chapter=[[s.v.]] ''Ozymandias''|title=Longman pronunciation dictionary|place=Harrow|publisher=Longman|year=1990|page=508|isbn=0-582-05383-8}} The four-syllable pronunciation is used by Shelley to fit the poem's meter.</ref> is the title of two related [[sonnet]]s published in 1818. The first was written by the English Romantic poet [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] (1792\u20131822) and was published in the 11 January 1818 issue of ''[[The Examiner (1808\u201386)|The Examiner]]''<ref name=\"Shelley1818\">\n{{citation\n| last = Glirastes \n | title = Original Poetry. Ozymandias\n | pages = 24\n | newspaper = The Examiner, A Sunday Paper, on politics, domestic economy and theatricals for the year 1818\n | location = London\n | publisher = John Hunt\n | date = 1818\n | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=TMPPAAAAMAAJ&dq=the%20examiner%201818&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false\n}}\n</ref> of London. The poem was included the following year in Shelley's collection ''[[Rosalind and Helen|Rosalind and Helen, A Modern Eclogue; with Other Poems]],''<ref name=\"Shelley1876\" /> and in a posthumous compilation of his poems published in 1826.<ref name=\"Shelley1826\" /> Shelley's most famous work, \"Ozymandias\" is frequently [[Poetry anthology|anthologised]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nShelley wrote the poem in friendly competition with his friend and fellow poet [[Horace Smith (poet)|Horace Smith]] (1779\u20131849), who also wrote a sonnet on the same topic with the same title. Smith's poem was published in ''The Examiner'' three weeks after Shelley's, on February 1, 1818. Both poems explore the fate of history and the ravages of time: even the greatest men and the empires they forge are impermanent, their legacies fated to decay into oblivion.\n\nIn antiquity, Ozymandias ({{lang|grc|\u1f48\u03c3\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03bd\u03b4\u03cd\u03b1\u03c2}}) was a Greek name for the Egyptian pharaoh [[Ramesses II]]. Shelley began writing his poem in 1817, soon after the [[British Museum]]'s announcement that they had acquired a large fragment of a statue of Ramesses II from the 13th century [[BCE]]; some scholars believe Shelley was inspired by the acquisition. The {{convert|7.25|ST|t kg|adj=on}} fragment of the statue's head and torso had been removed in 1816 from the [[mortuary temple]] of Ramesses (the [[Ramesseum]]) at [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]] by the Italian adventurer [[Giovanni Battista Belzoni]]. It had been expected to arrive in London in 1818, but did not arrive until 1821.<ref>British Museum. [https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=117633&partId=1 Colossal bust of Ramesses II, 'The Younger Memnon']. Retrieved 26 November 2015.</ref><ref name=\"Chaney\">{{Cite book\n| publisher = Rodopi\n| isbn = 9042020156\n| editor-last = Ascari | editor-first = Maurizio\n| editor2-last = Corrado | editor2-first = Adriana\n| title = Sites of Exchange: European Crossroads and Faultlines\n| series = Internationale Forschungen zur Allgemeinen und Vergleichenden Literaturwissenschaft\n| last = Chaney | first = Edward\n| contribution = Egypt in England and America: The Cultural Memorials of Religion, Royalty and Revolution\n| pages = 39\u201374\n| location = Amsterdam and New York\n| date = 2006\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vEr0r5oyrB4C&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=Egypt+in+England+and+America:+The+Cultural+Memorials+of+Religion,+Royalty+and+Revolution,+Sites+of+Exchange:+European+Crossroads+and+Faultlines#v=onepage&q=Egypt%20in%20England%20and%20America%3A%20The%20Cultural%20Memorials%20of%20Religion%2C%20Royalty%20and%20Revolution%2C%20Sites%20of%20Exchange%3A%20European%20Crossroads%20and%20Faultlines&f=false\n}}</ref>\n\n==Writing and publication history==\n===Publication history===\nThe banker and political writer Horace Smith spent the Christmas season of 1817\u20131818 with Percy Bysshe Shelley and [[Mary Shelley]]. At this time, members of Shelley's literary circle would sometimes challenge each other to write competing sonnets on a common subject: Shelley, [[John Keats]] and [[Leigh Hunt]] wrote competing sonnets on the Nile around the same time. Shelley and Smith both chose a passage from the writings of the Greek historian [[Diodorus Siculus]], which described a massive Egyptian statue and quoted its inscription: \"King of Kings Ozymandias am I. If any want to know how great I am and where I lie, let him outdo me in my work.\" In the poem Diodorus becomes \"a traveller from an antique land.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Siculus|first1=Diodorus|title=Bibliotheca Historica|location=1.47.4|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Diod.+1.47&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2008.01.0540}}</ref>\n\nThe two poems were later printed in Leigh Hunt's ''The Examiner'',<ref name=\"Shelley1818\" /> a weekly paper published by Leigh's brother [[John Hunt (publisher)|John Hunt]] in London. Hunt had already been planning to publish a long excerpt from Shelley's new epic, ''[[The Revolt of Islam]]'', later the same month.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n===Shelley's poem===\n{{multiple image |align=right | total_width = 320\n|image1=Ozymandias Shelley draft c1817.gif\n|caption1=A fair copy draft (c. 1817) of Shelley's \"Ozymandias\" in the collection of Oxford's Bodleian Library.\n|image2=Ozymandias.jpg\n|caption2=1817 draft by Percy Bysshe Shelley, [[Bodleian Library]].}}\nShelley's poem was published on 11 January 1818 under the pen name Glirastes. It appeared on page 24 in the yearly collection, under Original Poetry. Shelley's poem was later republished under the title \"Sonnet. Ozymandias\" in his 1819 collection ''Rosalind and Helen, A Modern Eclogue; with Other Poems'' by [[Charles Ollier|Charles and James Ollier]]<ref name=\"Shelley1876\">Reprinted in\n\n{{cite book\n | last = Shelley | first = Percy Bysshe\n | title = Rosalind and Helen - Edited, with notes by H. Buxton Forman, and printed for private distribution.\n | publisher = Hollinger\n | date = 1876\n | location = London\n | page = 72\n | url = https://archive.org/stream/rosalindhelenmod00she#page/72/mode/2up \n  }}\n</ref> and in the 1826 ''Miscellaneous and Posthumous Poems of Percy Bysshe Shelley'' by [[William Benbow]], both in London.<ref name=\"Shelley1826\" />\n\n===Smith's poem===\nSmith's poem was published, along with a note signed with the initials H.S., on 1 February 1818.<ref name=\"mainref\">Main, David M. (n.d.). Treasury of English Sonnets. Ed. from the Original Sources with Notes and Illustrations. ''The Examiner''. Shelley's poem appeared on 11 January 1818 and Smith's on 1 February 1818. Retrieved from https://books.google.com/books?id=VDIX7NHfyTAC&pg=PA328&dq=ozymandias+horace+smith+magazine&hl=en&ei=DS_PTK2uKoruuAOJgpUY&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=ozymandias%20horace%20smith%20magazine&f=false.</ref> It takes the same subject, tells the same story, and makes a similar moral point, but one related more directly to modernity, ending by imagining a hunter of the future looking in wonder on the ruins of a forgotten London. It was originally published under the same title as Shelley's verse; but in later collections Smith retitled it \"On A Stupendous Leg of Granite, Discovered Standing by Itself in the Deserts of Egypt, with the Inscription Inserted Below\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.potw.org/archive/potw192.html|quote=The iambic pentameter contains five 'feet' in a line. This gives the poem rhythm and pulse, and sometimes is the cause of rhyme.| author = Habing, B| title = Ozymandias \u2013 Smith| work = PotW.org| accessdate = 23 September 2006 }}</ref>\n\n===Comparison of the two poems===\n{{col-begin|width=80%}}{{col-break|width=40%}}\n<poem>\n'''Percy Shelley's \"Ozymandias\"'''\n\nI met a traveller from an antique land\nWho said: Two vast and trunkless legs of stone\nStand in the desert. Near them, on the sand,\nHalf sunk, a shattered visage lies, whose frown,\nAnd wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command,\nTell that its sculptor well those passions read\nWhich yet survive, stamped on these lifeless things,\nThe hand that mocked them and the heart that fed:\nAnd on the pedestal these words appear:\n'My name is Ozymandias, king of kings:\nLook on my works, ye Mighty, and despair!'\nNothing beside remains. Round the decay\nOf that colossal wreck, boundless and bare\nThe lone and level sands stretch far away.<ref name=\"Shelley1826\">Percy Bysshe Shelley, \"Ozymandias\" in ''[https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=MZY9AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&output=reader&authuser=0&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA100 Miscellaneous and Posthumous Poems of Percy Bysshe Shelley]'' (London: W. Benbow, 1826), 100.</ref></poem>\n{{col-break|width=40%}}\n<poem>\n'''Horace Smith's \"Ozymandias\"'''\n\nIn Egypt's sandy silence, all alone,\nStands a gigantic Leg, which far off throws\nThe only shadow that the Desert knows:\u2014\n\"I am great OZYMANDIAS,\" saith the stone,\n\"The King of Kings; this mighty City shows\nThe wonders of my hand.\"\u2014 The City's gone,\u2014\nNaught but the Leg remaining to disclose\nThe site of this forgotten Babylon.\n\nWe wonder,\u2014and some Hunter may express\nWonder like ours, when thro' the wilderness\nWhere London stood, holding the Wolf in chace,\nHe meets some fragment huge, and stops to guess\nWhat powerful but unrecorded race\nOnce dwelt in that annihilated place.<ref>Horace Smith. [http://www.potw.org/archive/potw192.html Ozymandias (Smith)] at potw.org. 1 August 2013</ref>\n</poem>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Analysis and interpretation==\n[[File:Statue of Ramesses II at the British Museum.jpg|thumb|150px|right|The ''[[Younger Memnon]]'' [[statue]] of [[Ramesses II]] in the [[British Museum]]. Its imminent arrival in London may have inspired the poem.]]\n===Form===\nShelley's \"Ozymandias\" is a [[sonnet]], written in [[iambic pentameter]], but with an atypical [[rhyme scheme]] (ABABA CDCEDEFEF) when compared to other English-language sonnets, and without the characteristic [[Petrarchan sonnet|octave-and-sestet structure]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n===Hubris===\nA central theme of the \"Ozymandias\" poems is the inevitable decline of rulers with their pretensions to greatness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cliffsnotes.com/study_guide/literature/id-245.html |title=MacEachen, Dougald B. '&#39;CliffsNotes on Shelley's Poems'&#39;. 18 July 2011 |publisher=Cliffsnotes.com |accessdate=1 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305043103/http://www.cliffsnotes.com/study_guide/literature/id-245.html |archivedate=5 March 2013 }}</ref> \nThe name \"Ozymandias\" is a rendering in Greek of a part of Ramesses II's throne name, ''User-maat-re Setep-en-re''. The poems paraphrase the inscription on the base of the statue, given by [[Diodorus Siculus]] in his ''[[Bibliotheca historica]]'' as:\n\n{{quote|[[King of Kings]] am I, Ozymandias. If anyone would know how great I am and where I lie, let him surpass one of my works.<ref>See footnote 10 at the following source, for reference to the Loeb Classical Library translation of this inscription, by C.H. Oldfather: http://rpo.library.utoronto.ca/poems/ozymandias, accessed 12 April 2014.</ref><ref>See section/verse 1.47.4 at the following presentation of the 1933 version of the Loeb Classics translation, which also matches the translation appearing here:  http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1C*.html, accessed 12 April 2014.</ref><ref>For the original Greek, see: {{cite book|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2008.01.0540%3Abook%3D1%3Achapter%3D47%3Asection%3D4| author=Diodorus Siculus|title= Bibliotheca Historica|others=Immanel Bekker. Ludwig Dindorf. Friedrich Vogel. In aedibus B. G. Teubneri|chapter=1.47.4|language=Greek|volume=1-2}} At the [[Perseus Project]].</ref>}}\n\nAlthough the poems were written and published before the statue arrived in Britain,<ref name=\"Chaney\" /> they may have been inspired by the impending arrival in London in 1821 of a colossal statue of Ramesses II, acquired for the British Museum by the Italian adventurer Giovanni Belzoni in 1816.<ref>[https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/aes/c/colossal_bust_of_ramesses.aspx \"Colossal bust of Ramesses II, the 'Younger Memnon'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002041823/http://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/aes/c/colossal_bust_of_ramesses.aspx |date=2 October 2011 }}. British Museum. Retrieved 10 January 2008.</ref> The statue's repute in Western Europe preceded its actual arrival in Britain, and [[Napoleon Bonaparte|Napoleon]], who at the time of the two poems was imprisoned on [[St Helena]] (although the impact of his own rise and fall was still fresh), had previously made an unsuccessful attempt to acquire it for France.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Hubris]]\n* [[Ozymandias (Watchmen)]]\n* Ozymandias (book by [[Thomas F. Monteleone]])\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Rodenbeck, John (2004). \"Travelers from an Antique Land: Shelley's Inspiration for 'Ozymandias'\". Alif: Journal of Comparative Poetics, no. 24 (\"Archeology of Literature: Tracing the Old in the New\"), 2004, pp.&nbsp;121\u2013148.\n* Johnstone Parr (1957). \"Shelley's 'Ozymandias'\". ''Keats-Shelley Journal'', Vol. VI (1957).\n* Waith, Eugene M. (1995). \"Ozymandias: Shelley, Horace Smith, and Denon\". ''Keats-Shelley Journal'', Vol. 44, (1995), pp.&nbsp;22\u201328.\n* Richmond, H. M. (1962). \"Ozymandias and the Travelers\". ''Keats-Shelley Journal'', Vol. 11, (Winter, 1962), pp.&nbsp;65\u201371.\n* Bequette, M. K. (1977). \"Shelley and Smith: Two Sonnets on Ozymandias\". ''Keats-Shelley Journal'', Vol. 26, (1977), pp.&nbsp;29\u201331.\n* Freedman, William (1986). \"Postponement and Perspectives in Shelley's 'Ozymandias'\". ''Studies in Romanticism'', Vol. 25, No. 1 (Spring, 1986), pp.&nbsp;63\u201373.\n* Edgecombe, R. S. (2000). \"Displaced Christian Images in Shelley's 'Ozymandias'\". ''Keats Shelley Review'', 14 (2000), 95\u201399.\n* Sng, Zachary (1998). \"The Construction of Lyric Subjectivity in Shelley's 'Ozymandias'\". ''Studies in Romanticism'', Vol. 37, No. 2 (Summer, 1998), pp.&nbsp;217\u2013233.\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource|Ozymandias (Shelley)|Ozymandias}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/romantics/poems4.shtml Audiorecording of \"Ozymandias\" by the BBC.]\n*[https://www.litpriest.com/browse/poetry/ozymandias-summary-themes-analysis/ Ozymandias Summary, Themes, and Analysis]\n* ''[https://www.owleyes.org/text/ozymandias Ozymandias]'' - Annotated text + analyses aligned to Common Core Standards\n* {{librivox book | title=Ozymandias | author=Percy Bysshe Shelley}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://rpo.library.utoronto.ca/poems/ozymandias |title=Percy Bysshe Shelley (1792\u20131822), \"Ozymandias\" |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher=Representative Poetry Online |access-date=2 August 2016 |quote=(text of poem with notes)}}\n\n{{Percy Bysshe Shelley}}\n[[Category:Poetry by Percy Bysshe Shelley]]\n[[Category:1818 poems]]\n[[Category:Ancient Egypt in fiction]]\n[[Category:Sonnets]]\n[[Category:Ramesses II]]\n[[Category:1818 in England]]\n[[Category:Historical poems]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the poems}}\n{{short description|Sonnets written by Shelley and Horace Smith}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox poem\n|name                = Ozymandias (Shelley)\n|image               = Ozymandias The Examiner 1818.jpg\n|image_size          = <!-- custom size for image (defaults to 220px)   -->\n|caption             = Shelley's \"Ozymandias\" in [[The Examiner (1808\u201386)|''The Examiner'']]\n|subtitle            = <!-- Subtitle or descriptor                      -->\n|author              = [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]\n|original_title      = <!-- Original title, if not in English           -->\n|original_title_lang = <!-- ISO 639-2 language code for original title, e.g. \"fr\" for French -->\n|translator          = <!-- Translator(s), if original not in English   -->\n|written             = <!-- Written: (date or year range)               -->\n|first         